3. Data Visualization¶

1. Barplot¶

This barplot displays the average total crashes for each state. You can easily compare the crash rates between states and identify which state has the highest average.

In [36]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))
sns.barplot(x='abbrev', y='total', data=df, ax=ax)
Out[36]:
<Axes: xlabel='abbrev', ylabel='total'>

2. Histogram¶

This histogram shows the distribution of total crashes. You can infer the most common range of total crashes and whether there are any outliers.

In [37]:
sns.histplot(df['total'])
Out[37]:
<Axes: xlabel='total', ylabel='Count'>

3. Relplot¶

This plot displays the relationship between speeding and alcohol consumption. You can infer whether there is any correlation or pattern between these two variables

In [38]:
sns.relplot(x='speeding', y='alcohol', data=df, color='red')
Out[38]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x277a9140dd0>

4. Pairplot¶

This plot provides scatterplots for all numeric variables in your dataset. You can observe the relationships between variables and identify potential patterns or trends. For example, you can see if there's any correlation between variables like 'total' and 'alcohol'.

In [39]:
sns.pairplot(df)
Out[39]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x277a8dd3910>

This plot provides a histogram along with a probability density curve. You can infer the distribution of total crashes, whether it's normal or skewed, and any potential outliers.

7. KDE Plot¶

The KDE plot of alcohol levels in car crashes suggests that the majority of car crashes involve lower alcohol levels, with a right-skewed distribution.

In [42]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.kdeplot(df['alcohol'], shade=True, color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Alcohol Level')
plt.ylabel('Density')
plt.title('Kernel Density Estimation (KDE) Plot of Alcohol Levels in Car Crashes')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

8. Jointplot¶

The joint plot combines a scatter plot and histograms to show the relationship between speeding and alcohol consumption. You can see if there's a correlation between the two variables and their individual distributions.

In [43]:
sns.jointplot(x='speeding', y='alcohol', data=df, kind='scatter')
Out[43]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x277a9ea24d0>
